China plans to launch eleven '''Huanjing''' ({{zh|s=环境}}) satellites for disaster and [[environmental monitoring]] ("huanjing" is Chinese for "environment"). The satellites will be capable of visible, infrared, multi-spectral and [[synthetic aperture radar]] imaging.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hongkong.usconsulate.gov/uploads/images/pAw-Xhv1qHB7cBNrkQbc3A/uscn_others_2008030301.pdf |title=Military Power of the People’s Republic of China |page=37 |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Defense]] |year=2000 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014082411/http://hongkong.usconsulate.gov/uploads/images/pAw-Xhv1qHB7cBNrkQbc3A/uscn_others_2008030301.pdf |archivedate=2008-10-14 |df= }}</ref>
The first two satellites, Huanjing-1A and Huanjing-1B, were launched on September 6, 2008 on a [[CZ-2C]] (i.e. Chang Zheng-2C / Long March-2C) rocket from the [[Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasaspaceflight.com/2008/09/delta-ii-launches-with-geoeye-1-chinese-launch-two-birds/ |title=First natural disaster monitoring satellites launched by China |publisher=NASASpaceFlight.com}}</ref> In a report dated 2008-09-03, the [[Associated Press of Pakistan]] indicated the launch would be conducted 2008-09-05 using a [[Long March 2C]] carrier rocket.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=51449&Itemid=2 |title=China to launch natural disaster monitoring satellites |date=2008-09-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928183455/http://www.app.com.pk/en_/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=51449&Itemid=2 |archivedate=2011-09-28 |df= }}</ref> On 2008-09-05, [[Aviation Week]] reported the first launch would be of optical imaging satellites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_generic.jsp?channel=awst&id=news/aw090808p2.xml |title=U.S. and China Resume Space Cooperation Talks |author=Covault, Craig |publisher=[[Aviation Week]] |date=2008-09-05}}</ref>
Huanjing-1C was launched on November 16, 2012 on a [[CZ-2C]] (i.e. Chang Zheng-2C / Long March-2C) rocket from the [[Taiyuan Satellite Launch Center]]. It is the first civilian Chinese remote sensing satellite to use a [[Synthetic Aperture Radar]] as imaging instrument. This S-band SAR was manufactured in Russia by NPO Mashinostroenia.<ref name='eureka'>{{cite web |url=http://danielmarin.blogspot.com.ar/2012/11/lanzamiento-larga-marcha-cz-3c-huanjing.html |title=Lanzamiento Larga Marcha CZ-2C (Huanjing-1C) |author=Marín, Daniel |publisher=Eureka Blog |date=2012-11-20| language=spanish}}</ref>
